title: For Sale:  RARE , Nazi marked French SACM 1935A 7.65mm French Long
postcontent:
A Rare Waffenamt marked French SACM 1935A chambered in 7.65 mm longue or French .32 long cal.   NO import marks!  This gun is absolutely correct and original.  It has a 4.25" barrel and overall length is 7".  An FFL or C&R is required for transfer. The gun is in overall excellent condition.  Only minor marks and scratches to the baked black enamel finish which is seen regularly on these guns.  The barrel is strong and the gun functions flawlessly.  However, I am not a gunsmith and therefore you should have it check by a professional before shooting.  Must ship to an FFL and is C&R eligible.  Buyer is responsible to know your local gin laws and ensure its safe to own in your area.  The cost is $450.00 PLUS shipping. 

about the gun.   According to Medlin & Huon ,Military Handguns of France, 1858 to 1958; “The German ordnance designation for the weapon was 625(f). The Germans maintained quality control, with the standards of manufacture the same as with French-made arms. The finish on the pieces remained the same, as did that of the magazines.” Magazine bottoms were blank once they started production but utilized the captured 35_A marked magazines for the first few thousand guns produced.  “The German military acceptance stamp is on the left side of the frame, between and slightly below the 1935A and SACM marks. The first group is stamped Waffenamt 655 (Eagle 655), starting with serial number B701A and  ending with serial number B1250A.  Afterwards Waffenamt 251 was then used (Eagle WaA 251), until the end of manufacture, the last pistol being serial numbered D4550A.”   Only a total of 23,850 German accepted guns were produced!  
Futhermore , Medlin & Huon state that; “During the run of Eagle 655 pistols, breech blocks and barrels have the 655 stamps. The change to the standard eagle with swastika on the barrel came with the change to WaA251. In the late 'B' series, numbering of the breech block to match the serial number began. Between C3341 and C6327, the barrel was given a two digit mark to match the last two digits of the serial number. This continued to the last of the German arms. Thus a pistol after C6327 should have military proof on the barrel, the last two numbers of the serial number on the barrel and breech, and Eagle WaA251 on the slide.” 
Therefore this gun having an early serial number of B3658A, is absolutely correct to have a non-numbered breech block as well as just having the eagle with swastika marked barrel and with a captured 35_A marked magazine!
